<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06129191 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06129191 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Abolhassan Bani-Sadr; ... Fired by Khomeini; PHOTO: L.Bruce Laingen; ... Wrote book's foreword  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  IRAN; KIDNAPPING; VICTIM; MEETING; PAST; PRESIDENT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The top U.S. diplomat held captive for 444 days in Iran stood face-to-faceTuesday with former Iranian president Abolhassan Bani-Sadr and told him hebore responsibility for an egregious violation of human rights.;    L. BruceLaingen was the senior diplomat at the U.S. Embassy in Tehran when Muslimstudents stormed the compound Nov. 4, 1979, and took 52 Americans hostage.Bani-Sadr was a protege of the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, who ousted thepro-U.S. government of Iran in 1979, serving as foreign minister and thenpresident throughout the hostage affair.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  EX-HOSTAGE CONFRONTS OUSTED IRANIAN LEADERDIPLOMAT CHALLENGES BANI-SADR MEMOIRS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;On the night you were taken hostage,&quot; Bani-Sadr told Laingen, &quot;I went toKhomeini and told him he had acted against Islam, against democracy.&quot;;   Bani-Sadr, exiled in France since Khomeini fired him in 1981, is in the UnitedStates to promote a book about the hostage affair and the domestic powerstruggles that marked the early days of Iran's Islamic revolution.;   Bani-Sadr, shaking Laingen's hand at a hotel reception, said he had acceptedthe job of foreign minister on condition that the hostages would be freedwithin a week. Several weeks later, when Khomeini prevented him from going tothe United Nations in New York to discuss resolving the hostage issue,Bani-Sadr resigned.;    Shortly thereafter, he was elected president.;   Laingen, standing very close to Bani-Sadr, handed him an envelope which hesaid contained some of the appeals he had written him in captivity seeking therelease of the hostages.;    &quot;I want to give these to you as an indication ofhow I felt then, and how I feel now,&quot; Laingen said.;    &quot;You bearresponsibility for an egregious violation of all precepts of diplomatic andhuman rights,&quot; he said.;    The two ended their brief remarks by saying theyagreed on one thing: Both want to return to Iran once it becomes free anddemocratic.;    Laingen told reporters later that Bani-Sadr, although he wasfighting for his political survival against the growing power of the clericssupported by Khomeini, didn't do enough to get the hostages freed.;    In &quot;MyTurn to Speak,&quot; Bani-Sadr charges that the clerics made a secret deal with theReagan campaign to delay the hostages' release in order to scuttle PresidentCarter's 1980 re-election bid.;    Laingen, who wrote a two-page foreword tothe book, said he does not believe in such a secret deal.;    But the book, hesaid, was an important historic document.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910508  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  15A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  427  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday May 8, 199100129191,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>